Adherents of free trade
From Cambridge — recently I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them had previously warned me: "These students are all strong supporters of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this was before even introducing the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that in real surveys, asking a representative sample — not Harvard students — the same question would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of trade restriction opponents to supporters is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not seem particularly surprising.
Because those with higher skills and better education often tend to support free trade more than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students had already anticipated their future prospects and made their decision accordingly.
Or perhaps they simply did not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately changed the format of asking the same question and emphasized the potential distributional effects of trade.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared completely, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
I started by asking everyone if they agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear — poof! — while adding $300 to John's account, and that the wonders of social engineering could add an additional $100 value to the class as a whole.
So would they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.

Clearly, students found it difficult to tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even when the overall economic pie had been made bigger.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, when free trade also leads to a similar — in fact, even more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
Students looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John each started a small competing business.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing a loss of $200 for Nicholas.
So how many students supported this change?
This time, most voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another assumption directly related to international trade.
What if John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by hiring child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the level of agreement with the change decreases in order with the above options.
Additionally, technological innovation can also place certain people in a more disadvantaged position, just like trade, and what is your stance on this?
Only a few students were willing to restrain technological development.
To almost everyone, banning the production of electric light bulbs to protect the jobs of candle makers is simply a foolish idea.
Therefore, what students oppose is not necessarily redistribution, but only certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the outcome of redistribution, we must know the objective context in which it occurred.
We do not get angry about the immense wealth of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett, even if some of their rivals have always had a tough time, probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich not through their own intelligence and hard work, but through fraud, breaking labor laws, destroying the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be completely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution that achieves its results by violating widely accepted moral standards domestically, then on what grounds can we feel comfortable about it when it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to achieve equality in the long run, with everyone ultimately benefiting, we are likely not to care about the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative effects to some people, we still want to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — — low-educated blue-collar workers — — we become worried about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They always tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to stupid and selfish trade protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Since they are unable to recognize that international trade can sometimes — — although not often — — lead to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to properly engage in public discussions.
But how can they defend trade vigorously when it is morally indefensible?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legalization of redistribution effects, we should not respond thoughtlessly with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons that need careful weighing, including the possibility that globalization may cause wealth deprivation more severe than that experienced by victims within the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions based on it.
And the approach of being overly enamored with globalization simply because it has made the cake bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
